<section class="bg-[#1e293b] py-20 md:py-28">
  <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-6">
    <h2 class="text-white font-extrabold text-2xl md:text-4xl tracking-[-0.02em] mb-10">
      What Is Flock Safety?
    </h2>

    <div class="space-y-6 text-[#cbd5e1] text-base leading-relaxed mb-12">
      <p>
        Flock Safety puts cameras on poles at intersections and along roadsides. Small. Solar-powered. Easy to miss. Every car that drives by gets photographed. Your plate number, vehicle make, color, and location get uploaded to Flock's servers automatically. Every time.
      </p>
      <p>
        Here's what your police department may not have mentioned: that data doesn't stay in Greenville. Flock runs a national network. Police from other states can search it. So can federal agencies. Every drive you've taken is in there.
      </p>
      <p>
        Your local police can't turn off the federal access. And neither can you.
      </p>
    </div>

    <!-- Pull quote -->
    <blockquote class="border-l-4 border-[#ef4444] pl-6 py-4 mb-14">
      <p class="text-[#f8fafc] font-bold italic text-lg md:text-xl leading-relaxed">
        "Your data is shared with agencies you don't control."
      </p>
    </blockquote>

    <!-- Fact cards -->
    <div class="space-y-4 mb-12">
      <div class="bg-[#0f172a] border-l-[3px] border-[#ef4444] rounded-r-md p-5">
        <p class="text-[#cbd5e1] text-[0.9rem] leading-relaxed">
          Two sisters in Greenville were driving a rental car when a Flock camera flagged it as stolen. Police drew their weapons and handcuffed both women. The car wasn't stolen; it had been improperly reported. They are now suing Greenville PD.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-[#0f172a] border-l-[3px] border-[#ef4444] rounded-r-md p-5">
        <p class="text-[#cbd5e1] text-[0.9rem] leading-relaxed">
          Flock says it deletes data after 30 days. Greenville's data goes to SLED, which keeps it for three years. When a reporter asked SLED for recent misconduct cases, they refused to answer.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-[#0f172a] border-l-[3px] border-[#ef4444] rounded-r-md p-5">
        <p class="text-[#cbd5e1] text-[0.9rem] leading-relaxed">
          In Santa Cruz, CA, agencies accessed local camera data 4,000 times on behalf of federal authorities before the city found out and cancelled the contract.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-[#0f172a] border-l-[3px] border-[#ef4444] rounded-r-md p-5">
        <p class="text-[#cbd5e1] text-[0.9rem] leading-relaxed">
          The Spartanburg County Sheriff who oversaw Flock camera deployments later pled guilty to federal charges: conspiracy to commit theft from federal programs and wire fraud. The man with access to your location history turned out to be a federal criminal.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-[#0f172a] border-l-[3px] border-[#ef4444] rounded-r-md p-5">
        <p class="text-[#cbd5e1] text-[0.9rem] leading-relaxed">
          Austin ran its own city audit and couldn't find evidence the cameras reduce crime. The system is designed to share data. There's no local switch to turn that off.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <p class="text-[#cbd5e1] text-base leading-relaxed">
      These cameras track everyone. Most of the people they photograph have done nothing wrong. All of them end up in the same database.
    </p>
  </div>
</section>
